# Amazon EC2

EC2 provides virtual machine instances for persistent compute workloads. Unlike [[aws/lambda]] (serverless, event-driven), EC2 gives you full control over the operating system, networking, and storage.

## Launch an Instance

```javascript
import { EC2Client, RunInstancesCommand } from "@aws-sdk/client-ec2";

const ec2 = new EC2Client({ region: process.env.AWS_REGION });

const { Instances } = await ec2.send(new RunInstancesCommand({
  ImageId: "ami-0abcdef1234567890", // Amazon Linux 2023
  InstanceType: "t3.micro",
  KeyName: "my-key-pair",
  SecurityGroupIds: ["sg-0123456789abcdef0"],
  MinCount: 1,
  MaxCount: 1,
  TagSpecifications: [{
    ResourceType: "instance",
    Tags: [{ Key: "Name", Value: "my-instance" }],
  }],
}));

const instanceId = Instances[0].InstanceId;
```

## Instance Types

Choose based on workload requirements:

| Family | Type | Use Case |
|--------|------|----------|
| General Purpose | t3.micro, t3.small, m6i.large | Web servers, dev environments |
| Compute Optimized | c6i.large, c7g.xlarge | CPU-intensive workloads, batch processing |
| Memory Optimized | r6i.large, r7g.xlarge | Databases, in-memory caching |
| Storage Optimized | i3.large, d3.xlarge | Data warehousing, distributed file systems |
| Accelerated | p4d.24xlarge, g5.xlarge | Machine learning, GPU rendering |

`t3.micro` is free-tier eligible (750 hours/month for 12 months).

## Security Groups

Security groups act as virtual firewalls for instances:

```javascript
import { CreateSecurityGroupCommand, AuthorizeSecurityGroupIngressCommand } from "@aws-sdk/client-ec2";

// Create security group
const { GroupId } = await ec2.send(new CreateSecurityGroupCommand({
  GroupName: "web-server-sg",
  Description: "Allow HTTP and SSH",
  VpcId: "vpc-0123456789abcdef0",
}));

// Allow SSH (port 22) and HTTP (port 80)
await ec2.send(new AuthorizeSecurityGroupIngressCommand({
  GroupId,
  IpPermissions: [
    { IpProtocol: "tcp", FromPort: 22, ToPort: 22, IpRanges: [{ CidrIp: "YOUR_IP/32" }] },
    { IpProtocol: "tcp", FromPort: 80, ToPort: 80, IpRanges: [{ CidrIp: "0.0.0.0/0" }] },
  ],
}));
```

Follow least-privilege: restrict SSH to known IPs, open only required ports. See [[aws/iam#best-practices]] for general security guidance.

## Key Pairs

Key pairs provide SSH access to Linux instances. Create a key pair before launching:

```javascript
import { CreateKeyPairCommand } from "@aws-sdk/client-ec2";

const { KeyMaterial } = await ec2.send(new CreateKeyPairCommand({
  KeyName: "my-key-pair",
}));
// Save KeyMaterial (private key PEM) to a file, chmod 400
```

## Elastic IP

Elastic IPs provide a static public IPv4 address. Associate one with an instance so its public IP persists across stop/start cycles.

## Environment Variables

| Variable | Purpose |
|----------|----------|
| `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID` | IAM access key for the EC2 client |
| `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` | IAM secret key for the EC2 client |
| `AWS_REGION` | Target region for instance launch |
